3. Start with the Basics

Always answer:

What is broken?
When did it start?
Who is affected?
Is everything down?
One server?
Multiple servers?
Only one service?

Example:

Website

❌ Login fails

API works

Database works

Static pages work

This immediately narrows the investigation.

4. Check System Health

First command:

uptime

Example:

load average:
18.0

If server has:

4 CPU cores

Load:

18

Huge problem.

CPU:

top

Memory:

free -h

Disk:

df -h

Disk I/O:

iostat -x

Network:

ss -tulpn

This gives a quick overview of system health.

5. Check Running Services

Example:

Website is down.

Check:

systemctl status nginx

If failed:

inactive (dead)

Start:

sudo systemctl start nginx

Check again.

Never assume the service is running.

6. Read Logs

Logs tell the story.

System logs:

journalctl

Follow logs live:

journalctl -f

Service logs:

journalctl -u nginx

Application logs:

/var/log/

Examples:

nginx

apache2

mysql

postgresql

docker

application.log

Always read logs before restarting services.

7. Check Disk Space

One of the most common production issues.

df -h

Suppose:

Filesystem

100%

Applications may fail because they cannot write temporary files or logs.

Find large directories:

du -sh /*
8. Check Memory
free -h

If swap is heavily used:

RAM exhausted

Find large memory consumers:

ps aux --sort=-%mem
9. Check CPU
top

Sort:

P

inside top, or:

ps aux --sort=-%cpu

Find:

Java process
Python script
Backup job

Consuming 300% CPU.

Now investigate why, not just how to stop it.

10. Check Network

Can server reach another server?

ping

DNS:

dig google.com

Routing:

ip route

Listening ports:

ss -tulpn

Firewall:

sudo ufw status
11. Check Application

Sometimes Linux is healthy.

Application is broken.

Example:

HTTP 500

Check:

Application logs

Maybe:

Database connection failed

Linux isn't the problem.

